  p.mt-3
    | For your property it is possible to calculate approximate figures
    | for your own situation.
  p
    | To relate this to your own property/properties firstly compare your fuel
    | bills in summer and mid-winter.
  p
    | This will give an indication of the cost of heating the hot water
    | used for baths, taps etc. and heating for the building fabric&nbsp;&ndash;
    | and it is also likely to concentrate the mind on such items as hot
    | water usage and for you to consider ways in which it is possible to
    | have hot water available when required and yet not have to store it for
    | such long periods of time through the day&nbsp;&ndash; it did mine!
  p
    | An allowance will have to be made for other items such as cooking if
    | the same fuel is used.
  p
    | Once the approximate heating for the building fabric has been
    | isolated then break down the areas of heat loss in winter, these will
    | be elements of the building exposed directly to outside air in winter.
  p The areas are likely to be external glazing, walls, roof and floor.
  p
    | To assess the loss through a specific building calculate the area of
    | walls, roof space, glazing and floor.
  p
    | This will mean that the proportion of heat loss of each element may
    | be estimated and related to the fuel bill (after the deduction of hot
    | water heating).
  p
    | But each element area firstly needs to be multiplied by the relevant
    | thermal transmittance or U-Value and then proportioned to the fuel bill.
  p
    | The new U-Value may then be estimated after the addition of
    | insulation and the calculation may them be made of the approximate cost
    | saving for the improved insulation to that element.
  p
