  h2
    | Proportioning the Fuel Bill and Calculating Pay Back
  p
    | The annual fuel bill incurred may now be proportioned using the
    | above information and the approximate payback of improved insulation
    | may be calculated.
  p
    | The Sutherland tables provides information on the cost of space and
    | water heating for domestic buildings using various fuels and for
    | 2-bedroom terraced houses, 3&ndash;bedroom semi and 4-bedroom detached.
  p
    | Their figures for October 2008 show a figure of &pound;2,365.00 for an oil
    | boiler providing heating and hot water to a 4 bedroom detached house.
  p
    | Let us assume that &pound;365 of this energy is for hot water and this may
    | be verified by the energy bill for summer when heating is not required.
  p
    | Let us assume that 10% of the heat is lost through ventilation and
    | cold air entering the house in winter.
  p
    | Then the remainder which is the heat losses through the fabric of
    | the house will be costing &pound;1800 per year in fuel bills.
  p
    | If we assume a 125 metre
    sup 2
    |  double storey house with
    | a roof space area of 125 metre
    sup 2
    |  consisting of 10mm tile,
    | loft space and 10mm plasterboard a 220mm wall with a 25mm air gap and
    | single glazing with wooden frames of 36 metre
    sup 2
    |  and the
    | building has four exposed edges.
  p
    | The proportions are as follow (as the numbers are for proportioning
    | only, the units are not shown):
  dl
    dt Roof
    dd
      | 125 metre
      sup 2
      | &nbsp;&times; U-Value of 2.6&nbsp;= 325
    dt Floor
    dd
      | 125 metre
      sup 2
      | &nbsp;&times; U-Value of 0.36&nbsp;= 45
    dt Walls
    dd
      | 156 metre
      sup 2
      | &nbsp;&times; U-Value of 1.56&nbsp;= 243.36
    dt Glazing
    dd
      | 36 metre
      sup 2
      | &nbsp;&times; U-Value of 5&nbsp;= 180
  p
    | The figures add up to 793.36 so the proportion of cost per element
    | related to an &pound;1800 fuel bill for heat losses through the fabric of the
    | building:
  dl
    dt Roof
    dd 325/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;737
    dt Floor
    dd 45/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;102
    dt Walls
    dd 243.36/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;552
    dt Glazing
    dd 180/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;409
  h2 Cost Effect of Improving the Insulation to the Roof
  p
    | Simply turn upside down the U-Value to obtain the R-Value, i.e. the
    | figure for the roof becomes 1/2.6&nbsp;= 0.38 and add the R-Value for the
    | new insulation and turn upside down again to find the new U-Value.
  p
    | The R-Value if not known is equal to the thickness in metres being
    | applied divided by the thermal conductivity of the material &ndash; the
    | latter figure will be given by the insulation manufacturer in units of
    | watts per metre &deg;C.
  p
    | So assuming we are going to apply 270mm of roof insulation with a
    | conductivity value of 0.04 watts per metre K,&nbsp;the R-Value would be
    | 0.27/0.04&nbsp;= 6.75 metre
    sup 2
    |  K per watt.
  p
    | Add this to the 0.38 R value above this becomes&nbsp;&ndash; 0.38&nbsp;+
    | 6.75&nbsp;= 7.13 metre
    sup 2
    |  K per watt.
  p
    | So the final U-Value is this figure turned upside down&nbsp;= 0.14
    | watts/metre
    sup 2
    | K which is a huge improvement on the
    | original figure.
  p
    | In terms of money saved and again related to the &pound;1800 fuel bill for
    | heat losses through the building fabric of the building this
    | would be:
  p
    | The new proportioned figure for the roof which came to 325 before
    | now after adding the insulation comes to 125&nbsp;&times; the new U-Value of
    | 0.14&nbsp;= 17.5.
  p
    | So the new financial cost of fuel due to heat loss through the
    | roof is now&nbsp;- 17.5/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;,1800&nbsp;= &pound;39 (compared with an uninsulated
    | roof financial cost of &pound;737 per year.)
  p
    | An exceptional saving per year, in this case, because the original
    | roof had no insulation at all so the addition of 270mm thick insulation
    | has made a huge financial saving on fuel cost.
  h2 Cost for Loft Insulation Material and Payback
  p
    | The cost of insulation material varies hugely at present and
    | consequently, of course, so do financial payback periods&nbsp;&ndash; the
    | cost of materials is driven by the energy suppliers having to hit
    | targets for carbon emissions.
  p
    | The general advice is that your energy supplier will put their
    | nominated insulation installer in touch with the building owner for a
    | survey and quote.
  p
    | But this is not necessary the cheapest way especially if the
    | installation is going to be DIY.
  p
    | At the moment for example B&amp;Q in conjunction with British Gas
    | are offering 200mm thick&nbsp;&times; 3.6 metre
    sup 2
    | of&nbsp;encapsulated fibre glass for &pound;3 a roll instead of the usual
    | &pound;34.88 per roll&nbsp;-&nbsp;so less than a tenth of the normal cost.
  p
    | So supply only for 125 metre
    sup 2
    |  would be 35 rolls at
    | &pound;3&nbsp;= &pound;105.00.
  p
    | As we have seen before the annual energy saving would be (&pound;737 -
    | &pound;39)&nbsp;= &pound;698 per year or &pound;58 per month then the financial payback for
    | the above example would be less than 2 months.
  p
    | The total cost assuming a subcontractor installs the work insulation
    | for &pound;200&nbsp;= &pound;200&nbsp;+ &pound;105&nbsp;= &pound;305.
  p So financial payback then is just over 5 months.
  p
    | However the insulation we are buying is 200mm thick insulation
    | instead of the 270mm insulation so it won&rsquo;t be quite as fast a payback
    | as that but not far behind.
  p
    | An approximation then of the revised figure would be 270mm/200mm x
    | &pound;39&nbsp;= &pound;52.65.
  p
  p
    | So still a massive saving of (&pound;738&nbsp;- &pound;53.66)&nbsp;= &pound;684.34 per
    | annum, or around &pound;57 per month saving.
  p
    | At a cost of &pound;105 for DIY insulation would be a payback period of 2
    | months.
  p
    | At a cost of &pound;305 for the work installed by a sub&ndash;contractor would
    | be a financial payback of about 6 months.
  p
    | The above is using fibre glass which is encapsulated and suitable
    | for 400mm centre joists.
  p
    | An alternative to fibre glass is rock wool or sheep&apos;s wool&nbsp;&ndash; the
    | latter is the most adaptable for cutting and carving around
    | in a roof space but the most expensive.
  p
    | So considering sheep&apos;s wool insulation, this is likely to be the
    | most expensive insulation but claimed to be the most sustainable by
    | their suppliers&nbsp;&ndash; I will let them put their own case below as to
    | why you should pay more for using this insulation.
  blockquote
    p
      | The key advantages of sheep wool insulation compared to man-made
      | are
    ul
      li
        | A better insulator compared to mineral wools, requiring 10%
        | less gauge to achieve the same insulating factor.
      li
        | Controls condensation&nbsp;- wool absorbs and releases
        | moisture; wool can absorb up to 40% of its own weight and remain dry.
      li
        | Glass fibre thermal performance deteriorates dramatically when
        | any moisture is present, wools performance is not affected.
      li
        | Wool absorbs harmful gasses, e.g. formaldehyde and locks them up
        | permanently, man-made emits gasses!
      li
        | Wool will last for the life of the building due to the
        | resilience of wool, glass fibre compacts and requires topping up every
        | 10 years.
      li
        | Wool is truly sustainable; a yearly clip of wool is available
        | as a by-product of the livestock farming.
      li
        | Wool is a &quot;Carbon sink&quot;, it actually locks up CO
        sub 2
        | ,
        | man-made pollutes CO
        sub 2
        |  in its manufacture.
      li
        | Very low energy required in its manufacture, only 15% of the
        | energy required to produce mineral wools.
      li Biodegradable at the end of its life.
      li
        | Safe to handle, no skin or respiratory problems typical of
        | mineral wools.
      li Supports economic deprived areas of the UK.
      li
        | Black Mountain only uses virgin UK wool, typically hill farmed
        | Swaledales and Welsh Black Face, hence the product is truly sustainable
        | and environmentally conscious and totally safe requiring no protective
        | clothing to install.
  p
    | The heat loss calculation in the example above uses a figure of 0.04
    | watts per metre conductivity for both fibre glass and sheep wool&nbsp;&ndash;
    | the suppliers of sheep wool state a conductivity figure of 0.044 which
    | is why they are claiming 10% improved performance.
  p
    | I am not at all sure of the source of their information they have
    | used that assumes fibre glass will require topping up every 10 years as
    | stated above&nbsp;- I agree more with the figure of lasting for 40
    | years as stated on the Energy Savings Trust website.
  p
    | This assumes that it is looked after and not crushed down with heavy
    | items in the loft which will reduce the insulation value of the
    | material.
  p
    | The Sustainability Centre&rsquo;s price for 100mm thick sheep&apos;s wool with an
    | area of 3 metre
    sup 2
    |  is &pound;21.11.
  p
    | So we would have to double up on the sheets for 200mm thickness to
    | get the same insulation value as the 200mm thick fibre glass&nbsp;&ndash; the
    | conductivity value for both the materials is about the same at 0.04
    | watts per metre K.
  p
    | For 125 metre
    sup 2
    |  42 sheets would be required and this would
    | have to be doubled to 84 sheets for the 200mm thickness.
  p So the cost would be for DIY&nbsp;- 80&nbsp;&times; &pound;21.1&nbsp;= &pound;1,688.
  p
    | If installed by a contractor let us assume &pound;200 again then
    | installed&nbsp;= &pound;1,888.
  p
    | Based on our annual saving of &pound;684 per annum this is a payback of
    | around 33 months or 2 years 9 months&nbsp;&ndash; a far cry from the B&amp;Q
    | special deal but using a more natural material.
  p
    | An alternative would be to use the 150mm thick sheep wool insulation
    | at a price of &pound;12.45 per metre
    sup 2
    |  which would considerably
    | reduce the installation costs and the reduced financial saving at the
    | same time&nbsp;calculated&nbsp;- still very significant.
  p
    | I can&rsquo;t find anyone who will subsidise the installation of sheep&apos;s
    | wool and this includes the insulation company nominated by my energy
    | supplier&nbsp;&ndash; but all other things being equal I would prefer sheep&apos;s
    | wool in my loft&nbsp;&ndash; but they are not all equal!
  p
    | So depending on the deal the financial payback is anywhere between 2
    | months and approaching 3 years.
  p
    | What about carbon dioxide payback as a direct result of the improved
    | insulation?
  p Using a saving of &pound;684.34 per annum for insulating the roof.
  p
    | If 4p per kWh is being paid for gas then 684.34/0.04&nbsp;= 17,100 kWh
    | per annum is saved or
  dl
    dt For gas
    dd
      | 17,100&nbsp;&times; 0.185&nbsp;= 3,163kg of carbon dioxide or just over
      | 3 tonne of carbon dioxide per annum.
    dt For electricity
    dd
      | 17,100&nbsp;&times; 0.537&nbsp;= 9,182kg or just over 9 tonne of carbon
      | dioxide per annum.
    dt For gas oil
    dd
      | 17,100&nbsp;&times; 0.252&nbsp;= 4,309kg or over 4 tonne of carbon
      | dioxide per annum.
    dt For fuel oil
    dd
      | 17,100&nbsp;&times; 0.268&nbsp;= 4,582kg or over 4.5 tonne of carbon
      | dioxide per annum.
  h2 Glazing Improvements
  p
    | The financial loss through the single glazing of the house was
    | calculated at&nbsp;&ndash; 180/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;408.
  p
    | The figures above were based on 36 metre
    sup 2
    |  of single
    | glazing&nbsp;&times; U-Value of 5 watts/metre
    sup 2
    |  K&nbsp;= 180 as a
    | proportioned figure.
  p
    | The addition of secondary glazing with a 150mm air gap is typically
    | likely to improve the U-Value around half to 2.5 watts/metre
    sup 2
    | K.
  p
    | One manufacturer claims that using 4mm low emissivity glass and a
    | 150mm air gap achieved a U-Value of 1.86 watts/metre
    sup 2
    |  K but
    | we will work with the figure of 2.5.
  p
    | The loss would now be 36 metre
    sup 2
    |  of secondary
    | glazing&nbsp;&times; U-Value of 2.5&nbsp;= 90.
  p
    | The financial loss after the secondary glazing improvement would now
    | be 90/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;204 per annum so this is a saving of
    | &pound;204 per annum.
  p
    | So if the addition of the secondary glazing was &pound;2,000 this would be
    | a payback of around 10 years.
  p For the carbon dioxide payback per annum:
  p
    | If 4p per kWh is being paid for gas and a saving &pound;204 per annum then
    | 204/0.04&nbsp;= 5,100 kWh per annum is saved.
  dl
    dt For gas
    dd 5,100&nbsp;&times; 0.185&nbsp;= 943kg of carbon dioxide per annum.
    dt For electricity
    dd 5,100&nbsp;&times; 0.537&nbsp;= 2739kg of carbon dioxide/annum.
    dt For gas oil
    dd 5,100&nbsp;&times; 0.252&nbsp;= 1,285kg of carbon dioxide/annum.
    dt For fuel oil
    dd 5,100&nbsp;&times; 0.268&nbsp;= 1,366kg of carbon dioxide/annum.
  h2 Wall Insulation
  p
    | Insulation may be added in the form of external insulation, internal
    | insulation or cavity wall insulation (assuming the building wall has a
    | cavity).
  p The simplest and least costly is cavity wall insulation.
  p
    | The financial loss due to heat loss through walls in the example was
    | calculated as follows:
  ul
    li
      | Walls &ndash; 156 metre
      sup 2
      | &nbsp;&times; U-Value of 1.56&nbsp;= 243.36
    li Walls &ndash; 243.36/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;551
  p
    | If 50mm of insulation is added with a conductivity of 0.04 watts per
    | then the R-Value would be insulation thickness divided by the
    | insulation conductivity&nbsp;= 0.05/0.04&nbsp;= 1.25 metre
    sup 2
    | K per watt.
  p
    | If this is added to the resistance of the existing wall which is the
    | U-Value of 1.56 turned upside down which is 0.64 then the sum of both
    | resistances&nbsp;&ndash; 0.64&nbsp;+ 1.25&nbsp;= 1.89 metre
    sup 2
    |  K per
    | watt.
  p
    | The new U-Value is now 1.89 turned upside down&nbsp;= 0.53 watts per
    | metre
    sup 2
    |  K&nbsp;&ndash; quite an improvement from a figure of 1.56.
  p
    | The financial loss now due to heat loss through the insulated walls
    | is:
  ul
    li
      | Walls &ndash; 156 metre
      sup 2
      | &nbsp;&times; U-Value of 0.53&nbsp;= 82.68
    li Walls &ndash; 82.68/793.36&nbsp;&times; &pound;1,800&nbsp;= &pound;188.00
  p So this will be a saving of &pound;551&nbsp;- &pound;188&nbsp;= &pound;363.00
  p
    | A specialist contractor should not charge much more than this for
    | the cavity wall insulation so the figure could be recovered in one year
    | or perhaps 1.5 years at worst.
  p For the carbon dioxide saving per annum:
  p
    | If 4p per kWh is being paid for gas and a saving &pound;363 per annum
    | then 363/0.04&nbsp;= 9,055 kWh per annum is saved.
  dl
    dt For gas
    dd 9,055&nbsp;&times; 0.185&nbsp;=&nbsp;1,675 kg of carbon dioxide/annum.
    dt For electricity
    dd 9,055&nbsp;&times; 0.537&nbsp;= 4,862 kg of carbon dioxide/annum.
    dt For gas oil
    dd 9,055&nbsp;&times; 0.252&nbsp;=&nbsp;2,281 kg of carbon dioxide/annum.
    dt For fuel oil
    dd 9,055&nbsp;&times; 0.268&nbsp;= 2,426 kg of carbon dioxide/annum.
  p
    | For internal and external insulation the installation cost will be
    | considerably more but the financial payback and carbon dioxide payback
    | would be similar unless thicker insulation was added than 50mm.
  p
    | A specialist builder/insulating contractor would need to survey the
    | site and quote for the work.
  h2 Draught Proofing
  p
    | In our calculation of proportioning heat loss we allowed 10% for
    | ventilation or cold air entering the home.
  p
    | The UK Building Regulations require that buildings are now much
    | better sealed than has been the case in the past. So well sealed,
    | in fact, that fan assisted heat recovery units are used in some houses
    | such as the Passivhaus in Germany.
  p
    | Older buildings are often not well sealed at all, as is the case of
    | my own property, and likely to have a heat loss even greater than the
    | 10% assumed in the example above.
  p
    | Brushes, foams and sealant may all be used to fill gaps etc. to
    | minimise the entrance of cold air.
  p
    | The Draught Proofing Association represents the major draught
    | proofing manufacturers and contractors in the UK and as it says on
    | their web site is one of the most inexpensive yet effective ways of
    | making the efficient use of energy.
  p
    | At the beginning of these figures I assumed &pound;200 per annum of the
    | energy bill was lost through ventilation or cold air entering the
    | house. If the leakages were reduced by half and &pound;100 could be
    | recovered and &pound;100 spent then the financial payback would be 1
    | year.
